{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_018KX7yXoaCwK53LQ6T6peLB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me plan this out. I need to:\n\n1. Design the mode control circuit in design.cir\n2. Write all testbenches\n3. Run the experiment loop\n4. Create plots and README\n5. Create xschem schematic\n\nLet me start by understanding the architecture and building incrementally. First, I need to calculate the resistor ladder values.\n\nThe resistor ladder: BVDD → R5 → tap4 → R4 → tap3 → R3 → tap2 → R2 → tap1 → R1 → GND\n\n\nNow I'm working out the voltage divider equations for each tap point, where each one represents a fraction of the total supply voltage based on the cumulative resistance below it. Each tap should ideally sit at the reference voltage of 1.226V. I need to reconsider the logic here—when the comparator trips, tap equals vref, and as BVDD increases, each tap voltage rises proportionally. So tap1 with the largest resistor fraction will reach vref first at the lowest voltage, which means R1 should be the largest fraction at 0.4904 of the total resistance.\n\nNow I'm working through the subsequent tap points: tap2 reaches vref at 4.2V, giving (R1+R2)/Rtotal = 0.2919; tap3 reaches vref at 4.5V with (R1+R2+R3)/Rtotal = 0.2724; and tap4 reaches vref at 5.6V with (R1+R2+R3+R4)/Rtotal = 0.2189. From these cumulative fractions, I can extract the individual resistor values.\n\nWait, I'm getting an inconsistency—R1 alone is 0.4904 of the total, but R1+R2 is only 0.2919, which is impossible. I need to flip my understanding of the ladder orientation. The taps are actually ordered from top to bottom: tap4 is closest to BVDD with the highest voltage, while tap1 is closest to GND with the lowest. So the voltage divider equations should reflect this ordering, with each tap accumulating resistances from the bottom up toward that point.\n\nNow I'm working through which tap corresponds to each threshold. Since