\nActually, the cleanest solution is to add a small resistor from the comparator output back to the tap node. When output swings HIGH, this resistor pulls tap toward BVDD, raising it slightly - so BVDD has to drop further to bring tap below vref, which creates the hysteresis I need. GND: The feedback resistor pulls the tap slightly toward GND, lowering it. This means BVDD must rise further to bring tap above vref. Wait, this is also hysteresis but in the wrong direction for the rising threshold...\n\nHmm. Let me think about this more carefully.\n\nRising BVDD: output is LOW (GND). Feedback R pulls tap toward GND. Tap = BVDD * ratio - V_tap * (feedback pull toward GND). So tap is slightly lower than BVDD * ratio. This means BVDD must be slightly higher to reach vref. The rising threshold is HIGHER than nominal.\n\nFalling BVDD: output is HIGH (BVDD). Feedback R pulls tap toward BVDD. Tap = BVDD * ratio + (feedback pull toward BVDD). So tap is slightly higher. This means BVDD can drop further before tap goes below vref. The falling threshold is LOWER than nominal.\n\nSo I've got the hysteresis direction right—rising threshold above nominal, falling threshold below it. The hysteresis magnitude scales with the feedback resistor relative to the ladder impedance at that tap point.\n\nThe problem is that feeding back to any tap corrupts the other ladder voltages since they're all interconnected. Even though the effect diminishes for lower taps, it's still not a clean solution. I could buffer each tap before the comparator, but that adds complexity. A better approach might be to use the comparator's internal hysteresis instead of trying to inject it through the ladder.\n\nActually, I could try an asymmetric differential pair design where the comparator output controls a small current source that biases one side of the diff pair, creating the hysteresis offset directly without touching the ladder.\n\nWhen the output is HIGH, I'll inject current into the non-inverting side to