ombination of upper and lower parts of ladder at that tap point), the current through the feedback resistor is small enough to not significantly affect other taps.\n\nAt tap4 (2.5V threshold): tap4 impedance = R4*R5/(R4+R5) ≈ parallel of lower (R1+R2+R3+R4 = 490.4kΩ) and upper (R5 = 509.6kΩ) = 250kΩ.\n\nWith Rfb = 20MΩ:\n\nI'm calculating the voltage shift at the tap when the comparator output goes high, and it's only producing about 33mV of hysteresis at the BVDD level—nowhere near the 200mV I need. Let me work backwards from the target hysteresis to figure out what feedback resistor value will actually give me the effect I'm looking for. I'm reconsidering the hysteresis approach—instead of using a massive resistor, I could use a weak PMOS transistor to source current into the tap node when the comparator output is high, keeping the tap voltage elevated to maintain that state. The challenge is sizing the transistor correctly to get the right current magnitude without making it too complex.\n\nActually, a cleaner solution is to add a switched resistor directly in the resistor ladder itself. When a comparator trips high, an NMOS transistor shorts out part of the upper resistor chain, which changes the effective tap ratio and creates the hysteresis effect—the rising threshold stays the same, but the falling threshold shifts lower because the tap voltage now reaches the reference at a lower supply voltage. Now I need to work out what value of Rhyst will give me that 2.3V falling threshold—I'm solving for the shunt resistance that creates the right hysteresis by reducing the total ladder impedance when the output trips high.\n\nBut there's a problem with this approach: shorting part of R5 changes the entire resistor ladder, not just the tap4 threshold. This means all the other tap voltages shift too, which could throw off my other comparator thresholds. Let me calculate how much tap3 gets affected by this modification.\n\nWhen I short out the hysteresis resistor, tap3's