{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01Fq6WcgufvEQMhrLXU8sUbs","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is that the parasitic model `sky130_fd_pr__model__parasitic__res_po` is being called with `w = {w}` and `l = {l}` but the subcircuit definition in the lib uses parameters like `w=1 l=1`. The problem might be that the parameter passing isn't working correctly. Let me check the parasitic model defined in the main sky130.lib.spice file.\n\nThe parasitic model defined in sky130.lib.spice:\n```\n.subckt sky130_fd_pr__model__parasitic__res_po r0 r1 sub w=1 l=1\n\n\n```\n\nInside the resistor model, it calls:\n```\nxc0 r0 r1 sub sky130_fd_pr__model__parasitic__res_po w = {w} l = {l}\n```\n\nThe issue is with the parameter passing `w = {w}` and `l = {l}`. The subcircuit definition includes capacitor calculations that scale with the width and length parameters, but the syntax for passing those parameters in the instance call might not be compatible with how ngspice expects them.\n\nLooking at the error message, it seems the parasitic subcircuit isn't being found when the instance is expanded. The problem could be a scope issue—the parasitic model is defined at the top level of the library file, but it's being referenced from within a nested subcircuit that was included later. This might mean the parasitic model definition isn't visible to the inner subcircuit scope when ngspice tries to resolve the instance. The parasitic model definition at the top level won't be included when using `.lib` directives since ngspice only loads content between the matching `.lib` and `.endl` tags. Block 04 worked around this by including the parasitic model file separately at the top of their library file, but that has the same issue. I need to either embed the parasitic model inside each `.lib` section or include it separately in my testbench. So ngspice actually processes `.include` directives at the top level even when using `.lib` sections—that's why the parasitic model gets included. The simplest solution is to add the parasitic model as a separate include statement in my testbench rather than relying on it being pulled in through the library file.\n\nLooking at the error more carefully, the subcircuit name resolution is getting mangled with the hierarchical path, which suggests the parasitic model definition isn't being found in the right scope.  I think the real problem is that `sky130_fd_pr__model__parasitic__res_po` is defined outside the `.lib` section in sky130.lib.spice, so it's never actually loaded. Let me just create a standalone parasitic model file and include it directly in my testbench.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1719,"cache_read_input_tokens":95225,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1719},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c97cdc95-3b2e-4d91-8a95-126c51f9e013","uuid":"7fedd32e-1fc7-4a69-8aa1-8ffac73c0dc9"}
