{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01X1DNu4BBtJMMvL8Sd8hmkp","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"HV PFET (W=20µm, L=20µm) at:\n- |Vgs|=1.0V: Id = 42nA (barely on, right at threshold)\n- |Vgs|=1.5V: Id = 4.08µA\n- |Vgs|=2.0V: Id = 14.9µA\n- |Vgs|=2.5V: Id = 31.5µA\n\nSo with |Vgs| = 1.5V: mirror supplies 4µA. That's reasonable for the comparator.\n\n\nNow I need to figure out the OTA's slew rate, which is limited by the tail current divided by the load capacitance. Let me estimate the parasitic capacitance at the c1o node—I'm looking at the drain capacitances of M1p4 and M1n2 (probably in the 50-200fF range for these HV devices) plus the gate capacitance of the next stage inverter.\n\nI'm calculating the gate capacitance contributions from both the PMOS and NMOS transistors of that inverter, which gives me roughly 1.58pF and 0.79pF respectively, bringing the total load capacitance to around 2.77pF. With a tail current of 4µA, I can now estimate the slew rate.\n\nThe slew rate works out to about 1.44V/µs, which means it takes roughly 2.1 microseconds for the comparator output to swing the full 3V. But here's the problem: the power supply itself is ramping at 1V/µs, so during those 2.1 microseconds, BVDD shifts by 2.1V. This creates a significant lag where the comparator output can't keep pace with the supply ramp, which is why I'm seeing the transition occur around 4.5V instead of the expected 2.5V. The solution is either to reduce the parasitic capacitance or boost the tail current to speed things up.\n\nTrying smaller inverter devices with W=20µm and L=20µm brings the total capacitance down to about 2pF and improves the slew rate to 2V/µs, but that still leaves roughly a 1.5V lag—not enough of an improvement. I'm also realizing that 20µm is actually the minimum width for these high-voltage devices, so I can't shrink them further. That leaves me looking at increasing the tail current instead.\n\nBumping the tail current up to 20µA would give me a 10V/µs slew rate and only 0.3µs to swing 3V, cutting the lag down to 0.3V. The problem is that four comparators at 20µA each plus the ladder current adds up to 90µA total—way beyond my 20µA budget. I'm also considering whether I can skip the buffer inverters altogether and feed the OTA output directly to the logic gates, but that risks crowbar current if the output doesn't swing rail-to-rail. Another option is using a latch instead of an inverter buffer to handle the switching more efficiently.\n\nActually, the cleanest solution is to drop the two-inverter buffer entirely and just use a single inverter after the OTA. The inverter acts as a high-gain amplifier, so the OTA only needs to nudge its input slightly above or below the trip point. But I need to be careful with polarity—if I connect things the wrong way, the output inverts when it shouldn't. I can fix this by swapping which side of the differential pair gets the reference and which gets the tap signal, so when the tap rises above the reference, the current flows the right direction. when c_o LOW → comp = HIGH when tap > vref ✓\n\nThis removes one inverter worth of cap load but still has the same gate capacitance issue since I still need one inverter.\n\nActually, the real fix is simpler: don't use a buffer at all and just use the raw OTA output with the logic directly. The OTA swings from near-GND when tap < vref to somewhere below BVDD when tap > vref, and even if it doesn't reach rail-to-rail, the logic inverters will sharpen the signal.\n\nBut for the current problem, the OTA output node still has 2pF of cap load from the inverter gates, and this remains even without the buffer.\n\nThe fundamental issue is that HV devices have enormous capacitances due to their 20µm minimum dimension, so each gate cap is around 0.8pF.\n\nLet me try a completely different approach: use the PMOS mirror output directly as one logic input instead.\n\nI could skip the inverter entirely and use c_o directly as \"comp\" in the logic without buffering. The logic gates would then load c_o with their own input capacitance of 2-3pF, but the slew rate is still limited by the huge capacitances inherent to HV devices.\n\nThe only way to get fast switching with these constraints is to increase the current. I'm wondering if I could dramatically increase the tail current but use cascoded current mirrors to limit quiescent current during active mode, or maybe reconsider how I'm using the bandgap reference.\n\nActually, let me step back and recalculate the timing constraint. The spec requires a comparator response time under 5µs, and at a 1V/µs ramp rate, that's 5V of BVDD ramp, so a 2V lag might be acceptable.\n\nLooking at the measurement data more carefully, the transitions are gradual rather than sharp. The raw OTA output starts rising around 3.34V and reaches mid-transition by 4.43V, while the buffered version through inverters shows the transition completing near 4.82V. The buffered comp2 appears to switch at roughly the same point where the raw output is transitioning.\n\nHowever, comp1 is the real problem here—it stays low until suddenly jumping high at 4.82V, which is way beyond the 2.5V target. I need to dig into why the first comparator's OTA is responding so slowly compared to comp2.\n\nLooking at the raw OTA output for comp1, it starts reasonable but then drops sharply around 2.14V and gets stuck near 0V for an extremely long time—all the way until 8.7µs—even though the input should be driving it high. Meanwhile, comp2's OTA is already climbing by 3.34µs, so there's a significant speed mismatch between the two comparators.\n\nThe root cause seems counterintuitive: comp1 has a larger input differential (tap1 at 0.49*BVDD versus vref, compared to comp2's 0.29*BVDD), which should make it respond faster. But instead, that larger differential is causing the input pair to conduct so much current that the current mirror gets overwhelmed—the mirror can't supply enough current to the output node to overcome whatever's pulling it down, leaving c1o stuck at near-zero for microseconds. The slew rate of roughly 1.4V/µs means the output takes about 2 microseconds to swing from ground to the supply voltage, which explains why the threshold crossing happens around 4.6 volts instead of at the rail—there's a consistent 2-volt lag introduced by this limited slew rate across all the comparator thresholds.\n\nBut comp2 shows much less lag than comp1, which is puzzling if the slew rate is the limiting factor. I'm realizing the issue might be more subtle—looking back at the c1o waveform, there's actually a voltage drop happening at 2.14 microseconds that contradicts what I'd expect from a simple slew-limited ramp.\n\nThe c1o node is being pulled down sharply around 2 microseconds and stays suppressed for an extended period. This suggests something is actively discharging the output node—either the PMOS mirror is turning off due to insufficient gate-source voltage, the tail current source is collapsing, or there's crosstalk from the other comparators interfering. At lower supply voltages like 1.5V, the PMOS mirror might not have enough overdrive to stay conducting, which would explain why the output gets stuck at a low voltage.\n\nOnce the supply voltage climbs high enough—somewhere around 1.8 to 2V—the PMOS mirror finally turns on and begins sourcing current. But there's a transient response during this startup phase where the mirror is still ramping up its current, so even though it's now active, it can't immediately pull c1o back up to where it should be. The output eventually recovers if the input conditions favor it, but the recovery is sluggish because the mirror current is building up gradually rather than switching on instantly.\n\nThe core issue is that the HV PMOS threshold voltage of 1.01V is too high, which delays the mirror's activation until the supply reaches roughly 2V or higher. Combined with this slow current ramp, the comparator output can't settle to the rail quickly enough before the supply has already risen significantly past the switching point.\n\nI'm reconsidering the whole architecture—instead of relying on an OTA with an inverter chain, I could use a CMOS Schmitt trigger where a simple inverter directly senses the tap voltage and provides hysteresis. The challenge is that a standard CMOS inverter's switching threshold tracks BVDD at roughly half the supply, but I need it fixed at vref ≈ 1.226V regardless of how the supply voltage changes.\n\nLet me try a more direct fix: speed up the comparator itself by increasing the tail current and simplifying the output stage. Reducing the tail transistor length from 50µm to 20µm would roughly double the current to around 5µA, which should significantly improve the slew rate. I can also eliminate the two-inverter buffer chain and use just a single inverter after the OTA, swapping the differential pair polarity so the output polarity is correct. This removes unnecessary capacitive loading and should help the comparator respond faster.\n\nNow I'm working through the actual numbers: with the tail current around 8µA at the gate voltage I'm using, and the load capacitance down to about 2.1pF with just one inverter stage, the slew rate comes out to roughly 3.8V/µs, which means the comparator transition would take around 0.7µs as the supply ramps at 1V/µs.\n\nBut this creates a lag of about 0.7V, pushing the threshold crossing up to 3.2V—well above the 2.7V maximum spec. The design is still failing the timing requirement, so I need to either push more current through or reduce the capacitive load further.\n\nI'm considering adding a regenerative latch with cross-coupled NMOS feedback at the output to create positive feedback and speed up the transition once the OTA starts pushing the output in one direction.\n\nAdding regenerative latch... I'm considering a simpler approach: use the resistor ladder taps to drive CMOS inverters directly, setting their switching threshold to match vref by tuning the NMOS/PMOS sizing ratio. The threshold voltage depends on the supply voltage, which means as BVDD ramps up, the switching point scales accordingly—aligning with how the tap voltage itself changes with supply. But this creates a supply-dependent threshold rather than a fixed one.\n\nLet me reconsider: I need the inverter to switch at exactly 1.226V when BVDD reaches its threshold voltage. Working through the CMOS inverter equation with specific values, I'm solving for the transistor ratio that makes this happen at the operating point. I'm reconsidering the approach—instead of using an OTA, I could replace each tap with a simple CMOS inverter sized to set the trip point near the reference voltage. The inverter gives me essentially infinite gain at the switching point and fast nanosecond switching, plus the capacitance is just at the output node rather than buried inside an OTA. The catch is that as the supply voltage ramps, the inverter's trip point shifts, but since both the tap voltage and trip point scale with the supply, I can maintain a fixed ratio by tuning the inverter sizing to match the supply-dependent threshold behavior.\n\nNow I'm working through the math to find what inverter ratio k I need to hit a specific threshold voltage. I'm setting the tap voltage equal to the inverter trip point and solving for the supply voltage at which they cross, then working backward to find the inverter sizing that gives me the target threshold at 2.5V.\n\nThe calculation shows k = 0.341, which means the PFET needs to be about 0.116 times the size of the NFET. But when I account for the mobility difference between electrons and holes, the PFET would need to be around 10.2µm wide—except the minimum PFET width is 20µm, so I'm constrained by the process limits and can't actually achieve this ratio.\n\nWhen I set both transistors to 20µm, the ratio becomes 0.227 instead, which pushes the threshold voltage up to 3.19V—too high for what I need. I'm realizing I need to find a way to reduce that ratio, and I'm second-guessing whether increasing the NFET length would actually help or make things worse.\n\nLooking at my options, increasing the PFET length would decrease its strength but push the threshold in the wrong direction, and I can't shrink the PFET width below the minimum. The core issue is that with these minimum-size high-voltage devices, the PFET is dominating the inverter behavior, making the trip point too high. I think I made an error in my threshold voltage calculation—let me recalculate using the correct |Vthp| value and the proper CMOS inverter trip point formula.\n\nNow I'm working through the math with the actual device parameters and the standard inverter trip point equation, substituting in the transconductance ratio and solving for what tap ratio I actually need to hit that 0.49 target.\n\nBut when I solve this out, I'm getting BVDD = 1.25V, which is way too low—the threshold should be at 2.5V instead. This tells me my formula approach isn't capturing the real behavior, since the inverter trip point and the tap voltage scale differently with supply voltage, and the threshold offsets are making the crossing point unpredictable.\n\nI think I need to abandon this analytical approach and go back to using an OTA-based comparator instead, but with significantly higher bias current to get faster response times. The quiescent current budget is 20µA at 7V, so I have room to push more current when the supply voltage is lower and the threshold crossing is happening.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the Iq spec applies to active mode when all comparators have already fired and the circuit is settled—the transient switching currents don't factor into that spec. The real constraint is the PMOS mirror current in steady state. At 7V with a 20µm/20µm mirror, the mirror gate-source voltage depends on what's happening at the comparator output, but once everything settles and the outputs go high, the mirror should turn off since there's minimal current flowing through the diff pair. Though wait—the tail current source sets a constant current regardless of the input conditions, so the mirror will always be supplying some quiescent current.\n\nIn active mode with all comparator outputs high and the tap voltage well above the reference, all the tail current flows to one side of the diff pair while the other side barely conducts. The mirror copies this current to its output, pulling the comparator output node toward BVDD. Adding up the four comparators at 5µA each plus the ladder current gives me about 27µA total, which exceeds the 20µA spec. I need to reduce the tail current, and the most straightforward approach is to increase the tail NMOS channel length to lower the current.\n\nIncreasing the tail length to 50µm cuts the current in half to about 2.5µA per comparator, bringing the total down to 17µA—well within spec. However, this creates a speed problem: the slew rate drops to roughly 0.9V/µs, which means the comparator lags about 3V behind a 1V/µs input ramp. That's too slow. I'm caught between needing low power and fast response, so I'm considering a different architecture entirely—either a switched-capacitor or regenerative comparator that only draws high current during the actual switching event, or adding cross-coupled NMOS feedback to provide regeneration once the output starts moving in the right direction.\n\nWith cross-coupled feedback, the regeneration time constant becomes very tight—around 2.8ns with a net transconductance of 1µA/V—so the output accelerates rapidly once it begins moving. The key is tuning the feedback strength just above the load transconductance to maintain proper resolution without immediately latching. I'll test this approach with the cross-coupled feedback and also try replacing the differential pair with a simpler single-inverter buffer stage.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"