{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01WJJ7kEHRDGwrBhZAH7p35W","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Still out = tap_in for all values in the first sweep! Even with an ideal current source tail. The mirror input `mi` does switch sharply at tap=1.2-1.3V (near vref). But the output `out` just follows the input.\n\nAnd there's a second set where the circuit is off (ctail=0, mi=0, but out shows something).\n\nThis is very puzzling. The output of the OTA is tracking the input voltage exactly. This shouldn't happen with a properly working current mirror.\n\nLet me think about this from a different angle. The NMOS mirror:\n- M_n3: gate=drain=mi, source=0. Diode-connected.\n\n\n- M_n4: gate=mi, drain=out, source=0.\n\nWhen mi jumps from 0.32V to 2.99V, the mirror current should change dramatically. At mi=2.99V, I'm checking if both transistors are in saturation—M_n3 has Vds=2.99V which exceeds its Vgs-Vth of 2.20V, so it's saturated. The question is whether M_n4 is also in saturation or if it's being pulled into the linear region, which would explain why out is following mi instead of being held at a constant current.\n\nAt tap=1.3V, out=1.30V, which is less than the 2.20V needed for saturation, so M_n4 is actually operating in linear mode. I'm calculating the current through M_n4 in this linear region using the triode equation, which gives a much lower current than the mirror would predict—this explains the voltage tracking behavior.\n\nNow I'm extracting the transconductance parameter k from the IV curve data: at Vgs=1.0V in saturation, the device shows 2.44µA, which lets me solve for k=110µA/V². Plugging this back into my linear region calculation gives I_n4=222µA at out=1.3V. But here's the critical issue—M_p2 has a gate voltage of 1.226V while its source (ctail) is only at 1.18V, making Vsg negative, which means M_p2 is completely off and can't supply any current to balance this.\n\nSo if M_p2 is off and M_n4 is sinking 222µA with no source current, the output should collapse to ground, yet it's sitting at 1.3V. I'm wondering if there's another current path I'm missing—maybe gate leakage through the oxide, though 222µA seems too large for that in a realistic scenario. Let me reconsider what's actually happening at the output node.\n\nActually, when out reaches 0V, M_n4 has zero drain-source voltage, so it stops conducting entirely. With both M_p2 off and M_n4 non-conducting, the output node floats—it can settle at any voltage. ngspice probably initialized the DC operating point near the tap voltage and converged there since no current is actually flowing to pull it elsewhere. The real issue is that ctail is stuck at 1.18V, below the 1.226V reference, which keeps M_p2 permanently off and breaks the current source entirely.\n\nThe ideal current source Itail should push 15µA from PVDD through the differential pair PMOS devices, but the measured ctail of 1.36V at tap=0 is much lower than the ~1.8V needed to sustain that current. With |Vthp| around 1.01V, the overdrive voltage is only 0.35V, which produces far less current than the intended 15µA—the quadratic relationship between overdrive and current explains why such a small Vov results in insufficient tail current.\n\nLooking at the PFET characterization data, at the measured ctail=1.36V with Vov=0.35V, M_p1 can only deliver about 2µA instead of 15µA. Meanwhile, M_p2 is completely off since its gate voltage (vref=1.226V) leaves it with insufficient source-to-gate voltage to conduct. This means all the current that does flow goes through M_p1 alone, but it's nowhere near the design target.\n\nThe discrepancy suggests either the body effect is playing a significant role that I haven't accounted for, or there's something about the circuit configuration I'm misunderstanding.\n\nWith PVDD at 5V and ctail at 1.36V, the PMOS source-to-bulk voltage is 3.64V, which creates reverse body bias and actually increases the threshold voltage rather than helping it conduct more current. This would make the PMOS even harder to turn on, not easier—yet somehow it's still delivering 15µA at this ctail voltage, which seems contradictory.\n\nI'm wondering if the simulation is getting stuck in an unreliable state due to the floating output node and marginal operating conditions. Rather than trying to fix this configuration, I should pivot to a completely different topology: an NMOS differential pair with a PMOS current mirror, powered from PVDD with enough current to handle the slew rate requirements.\n\nThe NMOS diff pair actually works well at the threshold crossing when both inputs are near 1.2V, giving a reasonable Vgs-Vth of about 0.4V. The real issue was just insufficient current causing slow slewing, but since PVDD current doesn't count toward the Iq spec, I can push much more current through. With an 80µm tail transistor at 1.226V gate voltage, I'm looking at around 32µA of tail current, which should give the diff pair enough drive to handle the slew rate problem.\n\nBut now I'm running into a contradiction—if the tail is at 32µA and each diff pair side gets 16µA, the required Vgs for that current is actually higher than what the input voltage can support, which would make the tail voltage negative and break the circuit.\n\nLet me recalculate the maximum current the diff pair can actually deliver at the given input voltage. With Vgs only 0.437V above threshold, each NMOS can only source about 10.5µA, so the total diff pair current maxes out around 21µA. That limits my slew rate to about 7.5V/µs, which translates to roughly 0.67µs for a 5V transition.\n\nNow I'm checking the H1=2.5V case—it switches at 3.17V, which exceeds the 2.7V spec. The NMOS diff pair is just too current-limited because the input signals are sitting too close to the threshold voltage.\n\nI think the real solution here is to go back to the PMOS diff pair but properly handle the body effect by tying the bulk to the source instead of PVDD. This eliminates the body effect entirely and avoids any forward-biased junction issues since the drain-to-source voltage stays within safe limits.\n\nBut wait—when the drain voltage drops below the source, the body-drain junction becomes forward-biased, which is the same problem I ran into before. The threshold for this is around 0.6V, so it only becomes problematic when the drain sits significantly below the source.\n\nIn a current mirror OTA, the output can swing all the way down to ground, which is well below the tail current source voltage, so forward biasing definitely happens. The standard fix in real IC design is to tie all PMOS bodies to PVDD in an N-well process—that's just how it's done.\n\nBut now I'm realizing that while body=PVDD solves the forward-bias issue, it creates a different problem: the body effect becomes huge. The source-to-bulk voltage increases dramatically, which pushes the threshold voltage magnitude way up. Let me calculate what |Vthp| actually becomes when the body is at PVDD=5V and the source is at ctail=1.2V, using the body effect equation.\n\nRather than work through the model parameters, I'll just set up a test device and sweep the gate-source voltage to measure the threshold directly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1771,"cache_read_input_tokens":338207,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1771},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c97cdc95-3b2e-4d91-8a95-126c51f9e013","uuid":"168c17e6-134a-4632-b75e-2b1df0c46b16"}
