{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01TKvVP6k95zcfKvvLvgB3DY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Same values without ngbehavior=hs. The \"current\" through the sense resistor = v(gate). This strongly suggests that the PFET is not conducting and the sense resistor is somehow being bypassed or the voltage source Vg is directly connected to the node. \n\nWait, I just realized something. Look at the circuit:\n- Vpvdd: pvdd = 5V\n- Rsense: pvdd → src (1Ω)\n- XM1: drain=0, gate=gate, source=src, body=pvdd\n- Vg: gate = dc (swept)\n\n\n- id1 should equal (v(pvdd) - v(src)) / 1, but if the PFET isn't conducting, v(src) should stay at 5V with no drain current. Yet src seems to be tracking gate somehow. I'm wondering if the print statement is accidentally using v(gate) for both columns, or if the `let` statement inside the .control block isn't working properly with DC sweeps. Let me try printing the raw voltages directly to see what's actually happening.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":386,"cache_read_input_tokens":348473,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":386},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c97cdc95-3b2e-4d91-8a95-126c51f9e013","uuid":"900382e0-57b3-4d56-a883-92d90691a8b7"}
