{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_014XkMs9F6u83bH3g3SvuKuo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Weird! At Vg=-5V: -i(vdd) = -4.873. At Vg=0: -i(vdd) = 0.126.\n\nThese don't look like currents either. -i(vdd) at Vg=-5V should be the PFET drain current at |Vgs|=5V with |Vds|=5V. From the earlier test where I confirmed PFET IV: at |Vgs|=5V: Id≈183µA = 1.83e-4 A. But the print shows -4.873.\n\n\nI'm noticing that -i(vdd) tracks almost exactly with v(gg) plus a constant offset of about 0.126, which suggests the probe might not be measuring what I think it is. Let me try using `.print` instead to get the actual current, or check if the PFET is wired correctly in the first place.\n\nLooking at the netlist, I see the issue now—the PMOS source and drain are reversed. With source at 0V and drain at 5V, the transistor has Vsd = -5V, which is backwards for a PMOS. I need to swap them so the source sits at 5V and the drain at 0V, allowing current to flow properly from the higher potential through the gate-controlled channel to ground. The PMOS is operating in reverse with drain at higher voltage than source, which causes BSIM4 to internally swap the diffusion roles. The body bias situation is also getting tangled up in PMOS conventions, so I should just go back to the approach that worked earlier.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":344,"cache_read_input_tokens":349452,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":344},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c97cdc95-3b2e-4d91-8a95-126c51f9e013","uuid":"a89b9f48-44f6-4582-a1c1-4e91123cd1bc"}
