{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01CGVz77xGuDjRmVh61gG8CA","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"3/16 specs pass. The main issues:\n1. **Threshold values empty** — ngspice `.meas` commands fail because hierarchical node names don't work in `.control`. Need to use the Python extraction approach.\n2. **Iq = 569µA** — the testbench measures current from Vbvdd which includes both ladder current AND the transient charging current. Need to measure at steady state.\n3. **Hysteresis values empty** — no hysteresis in current design.\n\nLet me fix the testbenches to use the Python extraction approach. I need to modify each testbench to save data files, then add Python-based metric extraction to the run_block flow.\n\nSince I can't modify `run_block.sh`, I need each testbench to print the metrics itself. The cleanest approach: have each testbench save data, then use a ngspice `.control` script to read the data file and compute metrics.\n\nActually, the simplest approach: have each ngspice testbench save a data file, then add a `python3 extract_metrics.py` call at the end of each testbench. But ngspice can't call Python.\n\nAlternative: modify the extract_metrics.py to run after the testbenches and print all metrics. I can add this to the run flow by updating the testbenches to save known filenames, then having the Python script extract everything.\n\nBut `run_block.sh` runs testbenches sequentially and collects their stdout. So I need each testbench to print its metrics directly.\n\nThe best approach: use ngspice's built-in math to compute metrics from the raw waveform data. Let me write testbenches that use `.meas` with the correct node names (not hierarchical — use the subcircuit ports directly).\n\nThe DUT outputs are at the top level: `bypass_en`, `ea_en`, etc. But the comp1-4 signals are internal to the subcircuit and can't be measured directly from the top level.\n\nHowever, I can measure the OUTPUT signals instead of the internal comp signals:\n- pass_off falls when comp1 fires (TH1)\n- bypass_en first rises when comp1 fires and comp2 hasn't (TH1 transition)\n- ea_en rises when comp2 fires (TH2)\n\nLet me use the output signal transitions to measure thresholds. The key: pick signals that have clear transitions at each threshold."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1002,"cache_read_input_tokens":452592,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1002},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c97cdc95-3b2e-4d91-8a95-126c51f9e013","uuid":"a45cbfda-4737-438f-8942-c1d90da42346"}
